The paper deals with algorithmic game theory and machine scheduling, which are topics that fall under the categories of cs.GT (game theory), cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.LG (machine learning), cs.AI (artificial intelligence), and cs.DM (discrete mathematics). However, since the paper focuses on the analysis of equilibria and social cost in the context of selfish users and machines, cs.GT (game theory) and cs.DS (data structures and algorithms) are the most likely categories. The paper also uses mathematical techniques to derive tight bounds, which further supports the likelihood of cs.DM (discrete mathematics) being a relevant category. Finally, the paper's focus on machine scheduling and resource allocation makes cs.AI (artificial intelligence) and cs.LG (machine learning) less likely categories.
